{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.07,0.02,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5194"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72747"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14036"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents for a medical. During the visit, she mentions a history of heavy menstrual bleeding since menarche. Her mother had similar symptoms. On further questioning, she states that she has episodes of epistaxis about once every two weeks or so and has a tendency to bruise easily. Her physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFull blood count (FBC) results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 79 g/L (120-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 69 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 230 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoagulation studies:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin time (PT): 12 seconds (11-13)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational normalised ratio (INR): 1.0 (0.9 to 1.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time (APTT): 33 seconds (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver function tests (LFTs), including bilirubin, are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate additional test to request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrinogen","Desmopressin trial","Direct antiglobulin test (DAT)","Vitamin B12 and folate levels","Von Willebrand studies"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a young female patient who presents with mucocutaneous bleeding (e.g., heavy menstrual bleeding, epistaxis). These suggest Von Willebrand Disease, the most common inherited bleeding disorder. Most cases show an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. It can be associated with thrombocytopenia and factor VIII deficiency, sometimes manifesting with an increased activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT). \u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand studies\u003C/strong\u003E, including factor VIII levels, von Willebrand factor (vWF) antigen and activity (e.g., collagen binding assay, ristocetin cofactor assay), can help confirm the diagnosis and guide appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinogen levels\u003C/strong\u003E can be decreased in disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) and liver disease. While hypofibrinogenemia can present with bleeding, vWD is a much more likely diagnosis and is more common. In addition, prolonged prothrombin time (PT) and/or aPTT can be seen in hypofibrinogenemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe direct antiglobulin test (DAT)\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the Coombs test, detects the presence of antibodies or complement proteins bound to red blood cells. It is primarily used to diagnose autoimmune haemolytic anaemia or to investigate transfusion reactions. However, in this case, the patient\u0027s symptoms and laboratory findings are not consistent with a haemolytic anaemia or transfusion reaction, making a DAT unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDesmopressin (DDAVP) trial\u003C/strong\u003E is performed in some cases of vWD (mostly type 1 which is due to vWF deficiency) to establish efficacy and response to desmopressin. In patients who are responsive and able to tolerate the therapy, this can be used in minor bleeding to raise vWF levels. However, it is not a diagnostic test and would not be appropriate as the initial investigation to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 and folate levels\u003C/strong\u003E are important in the evaluation of macrocytic anaemia, but this patient\u0027s mean corpuscular volume (MCV) is low. This indicates microcytic anaemia, making iron deficiency the most likely cause in view of the history of menorrhagia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder, with most cases showing an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.","The diagnosis is confirmed by Von Willebrand studies, which includes factor VIII assay, von Willebrand factor activity and antigen levels"],"references":["James PD, Connell NT, Ameer B, Di Paola J, Eikenboom J, Giraud N, et al. ASH ISTH NHF WFH 2021 guidelines on the diagnosis of von Willebrand disease. Blood Advances. 2021 Jan 12;5(1):280\u2013300.","Favaloro EJ, Pasalic L, Curnow J. Diagnosis and management of von Willebrand disease in Australia. Ann Blood 2018;3:31. Available from: https://aob.amegroups.org/article/view/4450"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72747"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72747"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-05T20:40:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-05T20:40:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5194"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (